{% extends "layout.njk" %}
{% import "macros.njk" as m %}
{% import "swatch-grid.njk" as swatches %}
{% set toc = [
  ["scale", "The scale"],
  ["swatches", "Swatches"],
  ["contrast", "Contrast"],
  ["scoping", "Scoping"],
  ["semantic-colors", "Accent and error"],
  ["greyscale", "Greyscale"],
  ["sass", "Sass API"]
] %}

{% block content %}
<h1>Colors</h1>
<p>
  Every color in the framework is derived from one variable, <code>--color</code>, using
  <code>oklch()</code> relative color syntax. A nine-step scale of lightness and chroma pairs is
  applied to that hue. Light and dark mode use the same scale, mirrored.
</p>

<section id="scale">
  <h2>The scale</h2>
  <p>
    <code>$lcArray</code> holds nine <code>(lightness, chroma)</code> pairs. Each becomes a
    <code>--swatch-lc-N</code>. Surfaces read the scale forward, text reads it backward:
  </p>
  {% call m.snippet("scale-mapping", "css") %}
--swatch-lc-1:  99%  0.018;   /* lightest */
--swatch-lc-9:  17%  0.055;   /* darkest  */

--surface-lc-N: var(--swatch-lc-N);
--text-lc-N:    var(--swatch-lc-[10 - N]);
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    In dark mode the swatch indices are reversed before the same mapping is applied, so
    <code>surface-lc-1</code> is always the page background and <code>text-lc-1</code> is always the
    highest-contrast text, in both schemes.
  </p>
  <p>
    The consequence worth internalizing: <strong>a pairing that reads well as
    <code>text-lc-N</code> on <code>surface-lc-M</code> in light mode does not automatically read
    well in dark mode</strong>, because the two schemes resolve it to different swatch pairs. Light
    resolves to stops <code>(M, 10 - N)</code>; dark resolves to stops <code>(10 - M, N)</code>. Use
    the table below rather than guessing.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="swatches">
  <h2>Swatches</h2>
  <form style="margin-bottom: 1rem">
    <label>
      <p>Base color</p>
      <input type="color" id="base-color-picker" />
    </label>
  </form>
  {{ swatches.swatchGrid() }}
</section>

<section id="contrast">
  <h2>Contrast</h2>
  <p>
    The scale is tuned so every pairing the framework itself uses clears WCAG AA (4.5:1) for normal
    text, at every hue, in both schemes. Worst-case ratios:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Pairing</th><th>Used by</th><th>Light</th><th>Dark</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-1</code> / <code>surface-lc-1</code></td><td>body copy</td><td>18.5</td><td>18.5</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-1</code> / <code>surface-lc-2</code></td><td>article, dialog</td><td>14.3</td><td>15.5</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-3</code> / <code>surface-lc-1</code></td><td><code>.secondary</code>, <code>.ghost</code>, <code>small</code></td><td>11.0</td><td>10.0</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-3</code> / <code>surface-lc-2</code></td><td><code>code</code>, <code>pre</code></td><td>8.6</td><td>8.7</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-3</code> / <code>surface-lc-3</code></td><td><code>small.chip</code></td><td>6.4</td><td>6.4</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-4</code> / <code>surface-lc-1</code></td><td>links</td><td>6.5</td><td>6.5</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>text-lc-4</code> / <code>surface-lc-2</code></td><td>links inside articles</td><td>5.1</td><td>5.7</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>primary-text-lc</code> / <code>primary-surface-lc</code></td><td>primary buttons</td><td>6.5</td><td>6.5</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    <small>
      Two pairings to avoid. <code>text-lc-5</code> on <code>surface-lc-5</code> resolves to the same
      color in both schemes. <code>text-lc-4</code> on <code>surface-lc-3</code> lands near 3.6:1,
      below AA for normal text.
    </small>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="scoping">
  <h2>Scoping a color</h2>
  <p>
    Rebind <code>--color</code> on any element and its whole subtree recolors. This is how
    <code>--accent-color</code> and <code>--error-color</code> are applied internally.
  </p>
  {% call m.demo("colors-scoping") %}
<div class="flex flip">
  <article class="card" style="--color: teal; flex: 1">
    <h3>Teal</h3>
    <p>Scoped with <code>--color: teal</code>.</p>
    <button>Action</button>
  </article>
  <article class="card" style="--color: crimson; flex: 1">
    <h3>Crimson</h3>
    <p>Scoped with <code>--color: crimson</code>.</p>
    <button>Action</button>
  </article>
</div>
  {% endcall %}
</section>

<section id="semantic-colors">
  <h2>Accent and error</h2>
  <p>
    <code>--accent-color</code> defaults to the complement of the base hue and is what links use.
    <code>--error-color</code> drives <code>small.error</code> and invalid inputs.
  </p>
  <div style="--color: var(--accent-color)">
    <label>
      <p>Accent color</p>
      <input type="color" id="accent-color-picker" />
    </label>
    {{ swatches.swatchGrid() }}
  </div>

  <div style="--color: var(--error-color); margin-top: 2rem">
    <label>
      <p>Error color</p>
      <input type="color" id="error-color-picker" />
    </label>
    {{ swatches.swatchGrid() }}
  </div>

  {% call m.snippet("colors-semantic", "css") %}
:root {
  --color: rebeccapurple;
  --accent-color: oklch(from var(--color) l c calc(h + 180));
  --error-color: maroon;
  --fallback-color: white;
}
  {% endcall %}
</section>

<section id="greyscale">
  <h2>Greyscale and disabled</h2>
  <p>
    A parallel chroma-free scale backs <code>--grey-surface-lc-*</code> and
    <code>--grey-text-lc-*</code>. The <code>.disabled</code> class and the <code>:disabled</code>
    pseudo-class swap the live scale for it via the <code>apply-greyscale()</code> mixin.
  </p>
  {% call m.demo("colors-greyscale") %}
<div class="flex">
  <button>Enabled</button>
  <button disabled>Disabled</button>
  <article class="card disabled" style="flex: 1">
    <p>An entire subtree can be desaturated with <code>.disabled</code>.</p>
  </article>
</div>
  {% endcall %}
</section>

<section id="sass">
  <h2>Sass API</h2>
  {% call m.snippet("colors-sass", "scss") %}
@use "@sparkstone/css/src/vars.scss" as *;

.thing {
  /* the ambient --color, at a given stop */
  background: cur-color(var(--surface-lc-2));
  color: cur-color(var(--text-lc-1));
  border: var(--border-width) solid get-border-color();
}

.fixed-hue {
  /* an explicit color instead of --color */
  background: get-color(var(--surface-lc-2), tomato);
  /* the same stop, chroma forced to zero */
  border-color: get-grey(var(--surface-lc-4), tomato);
}

.inert {
  @include apply-greyscale();
}
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    <small>
      <code>get-border-color()</code> is shorthand for <code>cur-color(var(--surface-lc-4))</code>.
      <code>cur-color()</code> reads whatever <code>--color</code> is in scope where the rule
      applies, so scoping still works.
    </small>
  </p>
</section>
{% endblock %}
